Replicating Perturbations - Correlations with Clusters

Mervin M Fansler

21 December 2023

Purpose

Here we compare the RPE1 with the K562 essential Perturb-seq experiments by computing the correlations between Z-scaled dWUI values across experiments. The expectation is that targeted genes in RPE1 will be most similar to the Z-dWUI of the cluster that the target was associated with in the K562 Perturb-seq data. In this case, we restrict ourselves to the genes that positively identified as significant genes in the particular target cluster.

However, we also expect that difference in cell types (K562 vs RPE1) and duration of experiment (6 vs 7 days) may contribute to variation in results, in addition to random variation in representation due to multiplexing.

Data

Loading

df_clusters <- read_csv(CSV_CLUSTERS, col_types='cccc')
clust_old2new <- read_csv(CSV_CLUSTER_MAP, col_types='c___c__') %>% 
    deframe %>% `[<-`('ntp', 'ntp')

df_genes <- read_csv(CSV_GENES, col_types='ccc') %>% 
    mutate(is_nonresponse=cluster_id %in% GENE_CLUSTERS_NONRESPONSE)
idx_genes_clustered <- df_genes %>% filter(!is_nonresponse) %$% unique(gene_id)

idx_target <- df_clusters$sgID_AB

wui_gene_rd7 <- readRDS(FILE_WUI_RPE1)

idx_sgID <- colnames(wui_gene_rd7)
idx_sgID_targeted <- idx_sgID %>% { .[!str_detect(., "non-targeting")] }
idx_sgID_ntp <- idx_sgID %>% { .[str_detect(., "non-targeting")] }

df_clusters_rd7 <- tibble(sgID_AB=idx_sgID) %>% 
    left_join(df_clusters, by=c("sgID_AB")) %>%
    mutate(target_gene=replace_na(target_gene, "non-targeting"),
           target_gene_id=replace_na(target_gene_id, "non-targeting"),
           cluster_id=replace_na(cluster_id, "ntp"))

sgid2cluster <- df_clusters_rd7 %>% 
    dplyr::select(sgID_AB, cluster_id) %>% deframe


dwui_gene_rd7 <- readRDS(FILE_DWUI_RPE1) %>% as.matrix
zdwui_gene_rd7 <- readRDS(FILE_ZDWUI_RPE1) %>% as.matrix

## common set of genes with zdwui values
idx_gene <- intersect(rownames(zdwui_gene_rd7), idx_genes_clustered)

wui_gene_ntp_rd7 <- wui_gene_rd7[,idx_sgID_ntp]

dwui_gene_target <- readRDS(FILE_DWUI_K562) %>% t %>% `[`(idx_gene,)
zdwui_gene_target <- readRDS(FILE_ZDWUI_K562) %>% t %>% `[`(idx_gene,)

df_wui_kd6 <- readRDS(FILE_WUI_K562) %>%
    filter(gene_id %in% idx_gene)

df_ntp <- df_wui_kd6 %>% filter(target_gene == "non-targeting")

wui_gene_ntp_kd6 <- df_ntp %>%
    dplyr::select(gene_id, sgID_AB, wui) %>%
    mutate(across(any_of(c("gene_id", "sgID_AB")), as.character)) %>%
    pivot_wider(id_cols=c("gene_id"), names_from="sgID_AB", values_from="wui") %>%
    column_to_rownames("gene_id") %>% as.matrix

wui_gene_target <- df_wui_kd6 %>%
    filter(sgID_AB %in% df_clusters$sgID_AB) %>%
    dplyr::select(gene_id, sgID_AB, wui) %>%
    mutate(across(any_of(c("gene_id", "sgID_AB")), as.character)) %>%
    pivot_wider(id_cols=c("gene_id"), names_from="sgID_AB", values_from="wui") %>%
    column_to_rownames("gene_id") %>% as.matrix

idx_targets <- colnames(wui_gene_target)

df_tests <- read_tsv(TSV_MW_TEST)

Summarize Clusters

## design matrix
M_target_cluster <- df_clusters %$%
    setNames(cluster_id, sgID_AB) %>%
    fac2sparse %>% t %>%
    `[`(idx_targets,)

## averaging matrix
N_target_cluster <- M_target_cluster %>%
    { . %*% Diagonal(ncol(.), 1/colSums(.), names=TRUE) }

## average wui, dwui, zdwui
awui_gene_cluster <- wui_gene_target %*% N_target_cluster
adwui_gene_cluster <- dwui_gene_target[,idx_targets] %*% N_target_cluster
adwui_gene_cluster[is.na(adwui_gene_cluster)] <- 0
azdwui_gene_cluster <- zdwui_gene_target[,idx_targets] %*% N_target_cluster
azdwui_gene_cluster[is.na(azdwui_gene_cluster)] <- 0

Correlations

CLUSTER_ORDER=c(1:18, "ntp")

sig_genes <- df_tests %>%
    filter(gene_id %in% rownames(zdwui_gene_rd7),
           !is.na(p.adj), p.adj <= 0.05) %>%
    dplyr::select(cluster_id, gene_id) %>%
    split(.$cluster_id) %>%
    lapply(function (x) x$gene_id)

df_pearson_zz <- lapply(names(sig_genes), function (clust) {
    idx_sig_genes <- sig_genes[[clust]]
    idx_sgID_rd7 <- filter(df_clusters_rd7, cluster_id %in% c('ntp', clust)) %$% sgID_AB
    cor(zdwui_gene_rd7[idx_sig_genes, idx_sgID_rd7], 
        azdwui_gene_cluster[idx_sig_genes,clust], method='pearson') %>%
        `colnames<-`(c(clust)) %>%
        as_tibble(rownames='sample_id') %>%
        pivot_longer(cols=-1, names_to="cluster_id", values_to="rho_pearson_zz")
}) %>%
    do.call(what=rbind) %>%
    mutate(cluster_id_new=factor(clust_old2new[cluster_id], levels=CLUSTER_ORDER),
           is_ntp=str_detect(sample_id, "non-targeting"))

q_values <- df_pearson_zz %>% group_by(cluster_id_new) %>% nest() %>%
    transmute(test_res=map(data, ~ broom::tidy(wilcox.test(formula=rho_pearson_zz ~ is_ntp, 
                                               data=.x, alternative='greater')))) %>%
    unnest(test_res) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    mutate(q.value=p.adjust(p.value, method='BH')) %>%
    dplyr::select(cluster_id_new, q.value) %>%
    deframe %>%
    `[`(as.character(1:18)) %>% {case_when(
        . < 0.001 ~ '***',
        . < 0.01  ~ '**',
        . < 0.05  ~ '*',
        TRUE ~ "NA"
    )}

df_pearson_zz %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=cluster_id_new, y=rho_pearson_zz, color=!is_ntp)) +
    geom_boxplot(position=position_dodge(width = 0.9), outlier.shape=NA, linewidth=0.25) +
    geom_quasirandom(dodge.width = 0.9, varwidth = TRUE, size=0.15) +
    geom_signif(y_position=0.78, tip_length=0,
                xmin=seq(0.75, 17.75, by=1), xmax=seq(1.25, 18.25, by=1),
                annotations=q_values) +
    scale_color_manual(values=c('black', 'steelblue'), guide=guide_none()) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0.1,0)) +
    labs(x="Cluster", y="Correlation (Pearson's rho)") +
    theme_bw()

ggsave("img/ed5j-rd7-kd6-cluster-zdwui-correlations-sig-genes.pdf", 
       width=6, height=4, dpi=300)
df_pearson_zz %>% filter(is_ntp) %>% distinct(sample_id) %>% nrow() %>%
    sprintf(fmt="We have %d non-targeting perturbations") %>%
    print()
## [1] "We have 112 non-targeting perturbations"
df_pearson_zz %>% filter(!is_ntp) %>% nrow() %>%
    sprintf(fmt="We have %d targeting perturbations") %>%
    print()
## [1] "We have 646 targeting perturbations"
df_pearson_zz %>% filter(!is_ntp) %>% dplyr::count(cluster_id_new) %$% summary(n)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   11.25   25.00   35.89   47.75  121.00
df_pearson_zz %>% filter(!is_ntp) %>% dplyr::count(cluster_id_new) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=cluster_id_new, y=n)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    geom_text(aes(label=n), vjust=-1) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0,0,0.1,0)) +
    theme_bw()

Conclusion

We find that every cluster has significantly higher correlations with the set of associated perturbations in the RPE1 cells compared to the non-targeting controls.
